== 4...a6 · Chebanenko Slav ==
The move 4...a6 introduces the Chebanenko (or Chameleon) Slav. Though it seems a small move, it prepares ideas of ...b5 (either to attack White's c4 pawn or to shore up Black's after ...dxc4) and eases the problems of developing Black's light-squared bishop, as now Qb3 can be met with ...Ra7.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Playing the Queen's Gambit|last=Schandorff|first=Lars|year=2009|publisher=Quality Chess UK LLP|location=Glasgow|isbn=978-1-906552-18-3|page=164}}</ref> 

The weakening of the b6 square, however, invites  White to simply push - '''[[/5. c5/]]''' is the most common response, gaining space on the queenside. In the resulting positions, it is very common for Black to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, where it is a lot more useful by eyeing White's center.

Alternatively, White can play '''[[/5. e3/]]''', solidifying their d pawn and adding their light-squared bishop to the fight, while accepting 5...b5. Less common are '''[[/5. a4/]]''', preventing ...b5, and '''[[/5. cxd5/]]''', releasing the central tension but leaving Black to show what purpose ...a6 now serves.

=== History ===
The Chebanenko Slav is named after Vyacheslav Chebanenko, a chess theoretician and mentor who developed the system in the 1970s after facing it against Fyodor Skripchenko<ref>https://en.chessbase.com/post/the-inventor-of-the-slav-system-with-4-a6</ref><ref>https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=2971400</ref>.

